body:
## Description

Compilation errors and warnings are currently printed in a way that is not very readable. I think that fixing this would improve usability and allow users to better understand compiler output.

Remix seems to be using the `formattedMessage` field from the Standard JSON output, which is really meant for console tools. Instead Remix should be using the individual components of the message, which are also included to allow tools to format messages their own way. `solc` itself uses that information to colorize the messages it prints to the console. In case of Remix colors would be nice too but as a GUI tool it has many more ways to make them more usable. For example it could make the source location a link and take the user to the affected line when it's clicked. Or it could hide included code snippets by default and display a button for unfolding them.

One more problem with printing the `formattedMessage` is that Remix seems to squash all the whitespace included in it. The compiler inserts this whitespace to align the `^^^^` indicators in the terminal. In Remix these indicators do not point exactly at at the right places in the included code snippets.

## Compiler output
A sample contract with a few bugs: (`C.sol`):
```solidity
contract C {
    function f() public {}
}

contract D is C {
    function f() internal
    override {}
}
```

This is what the output of `solc C.sol --color` looks like:
![solc-compiler-errors](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/137030/133339180-eb132c51-2557-4d87-8d1e-2593612c5708.png)

